<div class="artwork-content">
    <div id="artwork-details">
        <div id="tombstone">
   
    <p><strong>06. [Rug designs]. Christopher Farr. London, England; c.1995-1996</strong><br />       <p>Soon after finishing a postgraduate degree in fine art at the Slade School of Fine Art in London, Christopher Farr—whose father was an editor at <em>Design</em> magazine in the 1960s<sup><a href="3557#fn57" id="ref57">57</a></sup>—found his calling: modern rugs. Farr established his first shop in 1988, after training with world-renowned carpet dealer David Black. &ldquo;Fusing the ancient skills of weavers with contemporary designs,&rdquo;<sup><a href="3557#fn58" id="ref58">58</a></sup> Farr and his business partner Matthew Bourne have collaborated with contemporary artists and designers such as Romeo Gigli, Kate Blee and the family of Gunta Stölzl,<sup><a href="3557#fn59" id="ref59">59</a></sup> while continuing to source fabric from rural villages in Turkey, India and Nepal.<sup><a href="3557#fn60" id="ref60">60</a></sup></p>
<p>Samples of Farr&rsquo;s abstract designs below include one recalling Rothko&rsquo;s bold rectangular forms and another, Franz Kline&rsquo;s spirited strokes.</p>


<br />
<p><sup id="fn57">57. Dinah Hall, &ldquo;Inside the rug designer Christopher Farr&rsquo;s colourful Californian home, <em>The Telegraph</em>, accessed 07/03/2015, http://www.telegraph.co.uk/lifestyle/interiors/11301590/Inside-the-rug-designer-Christopher-Farrs-colourful-Californian-home.html <a href="3557#ref57" title="Jump back to footnote 57 in the text.">↩</a></p>
<p><sup id="fn58">58. Ibid.<a href="3557#ref58" title="Jump back to footnote 58 in the text.">↩</a></p>
<p><sup id="fn59">59. <em>Christopherfarr.com</em>, accessed 07/03/2015, http://christopherfarr.com/history<a href="3557#ref60" title="Jump back to footnote 60 in the text.">↩</a></p>
<p><sup id="fn60">60.  &ldquo;Q&amp;A With Christopher Farr,&rdquo; <em>Dwell</em>, accessed 07/03/2015, http://www.dwell.com/interviews/article/q-christopher-farr<a href="3557#ref60" title="Jump back to footnote 60 in the text.">↩</a></p><br /><br />
    	 "Tools of the Trade: 19th- and 20th-Century Architectural Trade Catalogs," Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, August 4, 2015-October 12, 2015.<br />
